WEBVTT

00:00:07.130 --> 00:00:08.800
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:11.780
In this video I want to finish
up our work with the ratio

00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:14.270
test, and in particular in
this video, I'd like to

00:00:14.270 --> 00:00:16.000
address something
that Professor

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.200
Jerison talked about.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:20.070
In, when he was talking about
these Taylor series, he was

00:00:20.070 --> 00:00:22.880
talking about the radius of
convergence at some point.

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:25.760
And he didn't go into it very
specifically, but he was

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:28.620
essentially saying for some
values of x-- you'll have a

00:00:28.620 --> 00:00:32.540
series that has x to the n in
it-- for some values of x it

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:34.780
will converge, and for some
values it will diverge.

00:00:34.780 --> 00:00:40.400
So let me just remind you of
something you already know.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:47.353
So, if we consider the
series x to the n.

00:00:47.353 --> 00:00:48.620
Right?

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:51.990
This is the geometric series and
we know that this is equal

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:56.880
to 1 over 1 minus x if the
absolute value of x

00:00:56.880 --> 00:00:58.085
is less than 1.

00:00:58.085 --> 00:00:59.230
Right?

00:00:59.230 --> 00:01:02.310
And so we know that this
series is finite.

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:05.400
This sum converges.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:08.520
To whatever value, If I plug in
x here, it converges when

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:10.660
absolute value of x
is less than 1.

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:14.220
And it diverges when absolute
value of x is bigger than 1.

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:16.830
And we're not going to address
when the absolute

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:18.250
value of x equals 1.

00:01:18.250 --> 00:01:20.550
We won't address that case.

00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:23.240
But, the point I want to make
it is that for some values

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:25.395
this series converges,
and for some

00:01:25.395 --> 00:01:27.500
values this series diverges.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:30.680
And those values can give us
the radius of convergence.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:34.370
So the radius of convergence of
this series is actually 1,

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:37.530
because x goes from 0 up to 1,
and then from 0 down to 1.

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:40.860
If you think about it, radius
might be a confusing term, but

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:44.260
can think about it as a circle
and one dimension less than

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:46.820
maybe you usually think
about it as a circle.

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:49.840
If this is the number line,
we're going from 0 up to 1 and

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:50.840
down to minus 1.

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:53.020
So you're going in one direction
up to 1 and one

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:54.640
direction down to minus 1.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:01:56.740
So this is radius 1.

00:01:56.740 --> 00:01:59.390
r is equal to 1.

00:01:59.390 --> 00:02:03.130
So what I want to do is figure
out how I can use the ratio

00:02:03.130 --> 00:02:07.230
test to tell me the radius of
convergence of other series,

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:09.255
other power series,
besides this one.

00:02:09.255 --> 00:02:10.320
OK?

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.770
So we're really interested in
for what values of x do these

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:14.760
power series converge.

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:15.050
OK?

00:02:15.050 --> 00:02:17.050
And how we're going to do
that, is we're going to

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:20.390
directly use the ratio test. And
one thing that I mentioned

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:23.440
in the other case, in the other
ratio test video, is I

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.460
said you want to have your
terms be positive.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:31.000
And so just to make this easy
on ourselves, when we do the

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:32.970
ratio test we're just going
to take the absolute

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:35.250
value of the ratio.

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:37.480
And that will be sufficient for
our purposes to determine

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:39.290
the radius of convergence.

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:41.090
I don't want to go into
anything more

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:42.160
complicated than that.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:45.737
So we'll see as we do these
examples, we're just gonna,

00:02:45.737 --> 00:02:48.010
we're just gonna take the
absolute value of the ratio.

00:02:48.010 --> 00:02:50.110
So let's actually start
off right away

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.820
with doing some examples.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:54.590
And each time I do an
example, I'm asking

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:55.840
the following question.

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:00.810
Actually, I was going to say
for what values of x, but

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:02.050
that's not quite true.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:13.150
I just want to know what is the
radius of convergence for

00:03:13.150 --> 00:03:15.880
each power series?

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.450
So I'm not going to write it up
every time, but this is the

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:21.560
question we want to
be thinking about.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:23.810
So I'm going to write down some
power series and we're

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:25.020
going to see what
is the radius of

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:26.680
convergence for each of those.

00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:29.800
I was going to write find the
values of x for which the

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:33.180
power series converge, but
that's not quite true because

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:36.160
sometimes it will actually
converge on one

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:38.160
or both of the endpoints.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:39.650
We're not going to deal
with that one.

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:41.720
But sometimes it will converge
on one or the

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.170
other of the endpoints.

00:03:44.170 --> 00:03:46.500
So I'm going to be asking the
question, find the radius of

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:47.820
convergence.

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:50.620
So let's do an example, and I'll
show you how it applies

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:54.900
to the ratio test. Then we'll
go from there and do some

00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:55.460
other examples.

00:03:55.460 --> 00:03:58.840
So let's consider the series
x over 2 to the n.

00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:00.870
This will be an easy one.

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:03.540
Now the ratio test
told us that we

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:04.900
examine a certain limit.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:07.620
We examine the limit as
n goes to infinity.

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:10.800
It said a sub n plus
1 over a sub n.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:15.600
Well if we think of this whole
thing as a sub n, then a sub n

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:21.050
plus 1 is x over 2
to the n plus 1.

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:26.910
And then we have to divide
by x over 2 to the n.

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:29.620
So let me just make sure
we understand that.

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:34.390
The way we, the way we want to
think about this is as if the

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:40.520
a sub n is actually a function
of x that also depends on n.

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:44.640
OK, so a sub n, we think of it
as x over 2 raised to the n.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.090
So a sub n plus 1 is x over
2 raised to the n plus 1.

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:51.770
a sub n is x over 2
raised to the n.

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:54.530
OK, and so this looks exactly
like the ratio test we had

00:04:54.530 --> 00:04:58.870
before, I told you I'm going to
put absolute values on it.

00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:00.100
And so let me simplify this.

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.510
I put the division sign maybe
kind of funny 'cause I wanted

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:04.520
to have it in a row there.

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:07.830
I apologize if that made
it more confusing.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:13.410
So this equals, well I have x to
the n plus 1 over x to the

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:18.370
n times 2 to the n-- this come
to the numerator because it's

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:20.640
in the denominator of
the denominator--

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:23.580
over-- and this goes to
the denominator--

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:25.270
2 to the n plus 1.

00:05:25.270 --> 00:05:26.570
Now what is this?

00:05:26.570 --> 00:05:29.680
This whole thing converges
to what?

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:33.950
2 to the n over 2 to the n plus
1 simplifies to 1/2, and

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:37.020
x to the n plus 1 over x
the n simplifies to x.

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.790
So this is equal to absolute
value of x over 2.

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:43.490
Now we haven't shown how the
ratio test is going to help us

00:05:43.490 --> 00:05:45.580
find the radius of
convergence.

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:47.060
And here's where we're going
to see it working.

00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:51.530
If we want to know that, we
want to draw a conclusion

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:54.150
about the convergence
of this series.

00:05:54.150 --> 00:05:59.790
We know that if this limit is
less than 1, that the series

00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:01.830
definitely converges.

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:05.320
So if I take my limit when I'm
all done, and I set it less

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:10.030
than 1, and I solve for absolute
value of x, then that

00:06:10.030 --> 00:06:13.640
will tell me exactly what the
radius of convergence is.

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:16.070
Let me go through that
one more time.

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:19.560
We knew that if we had this
series in terms of a sub n,

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:22.610
and we looked at the ratio and
we took the limit of these

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:26.450
ratios, and in the limit the
value was will strictly less

00:06:26.450 --> 00:06:29.990
than 1, we know the
series converges.

00:06:29.990 --> 00:06:32.700
So now we have this thing in
terms of x, but ultimately

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.450
it's the same process.

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:36.890
And we get to a place where
we know the limit.

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:39.140
It depends on x.

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:43.310
And so the limit will be less
than 1, exactly where this

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:44.540
thing is less than 1.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:45.930
Right?

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:47.870
So it's now in terms of x.

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:49.660
This less than 1 I'm putting
in at the end.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:52.070
This is where the ratio
test is happening.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:53.620
So what does this tell us?

00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:54.980
Where does this converge?

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:57.640
It converges when absolute value
of x over 2 is less than

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:00.580
1, which means absolute value
of x is less than 2.

00:07:00.580 --> 00:07:01.830
Right?

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:08.640
I just multiply by 2 'cause
absolute value of 2 is 2.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:11.950
I don't have to worry about
if 2 is negative.

00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:13.860
So the absolute value
of x is less than 2.

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:17.820
That tells me the radius of
convergence is actually 2.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:19.610
Now this shouldn't surprise
us really.

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:23.550
Because this is, in fact, a
geometric series, and we know

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:26.165
that the usual geometric series
converges when the

00:07:26.165 --> 00:07:28.050
absolute value of x
is less than 1.

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:30.780
So it's not surprising, and
actually fits in with what we

00:07:30.780 --> 00:07:33.700
already know, that if this thing
on the inside, if its

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:37.510
absolute value is less than 1,
that the thing will converge.

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:39.330
So that that means absolute
value of x has to

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:40.660
be less than 2.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:43.715
So again, hopefully this fits
in with the knowledge we

00:07:43.715 --> 00:07:46.070
already have. Hopefully it makes
sense to you, what we're

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:46.960
trying to do.

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:51.056
And so let's do another couple
of examples to make this, make

00:07:51.056 --> 00:07:52.306
this solidify.

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:55.780
All right what were
my other examples?

00:07:55.780 --> 00:07:58.250
OK, let's do this one.

00:07:58.250 --> 00:08:02.360
x to the n over n factorial.

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:08.806
All right, so now our a sub
n, when we look at this

00:08:08.806 --> 00:08:08.932
geometric-- geometric? this is
not geometric-- when we look

00:08:08.932 --> 00:08:13.220
at the series, our a sub
n is going to be x to

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:14.940
the n over n factorial.

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:18.100
And so when we take our whole
limit, the thing that's going

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:20.210
to happen is we're going to have
something in terms of x

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:20.950
at the end.

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:24.320
Our goal is to find for what
values of x is that thing we

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:26.310
have less than 1?

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:28.770
Again this is where we're
using the ratio test.

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:30.340
So let's look at this thing.

00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:33.650
We want to look at the limit
as n goes to infinity.

00:08:33.650 --> 00:08:39.870
Well, a sub n plus 1 is going
to be x to the n plus 1 over

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:43.260
the quantity n plus
1 factorial.

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:44.855
I'm going to put the absolute
value over there.

00:08:44.855 --> 00:08:48.360
Now I'm going to multiply
it by 1 over a sub n.

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:52.200
So this is actually a sub n, so
1 over that is n factorial

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:55.650
over x to the n.

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:57.960
Now we have to be a little
careful here.

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:00.820
I want to make sure everybody
understands something.

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:04.950
n factorial is n times n minus
1 times n minus 2 times n

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:07.830
minus 3 all the way down.

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:12.930
n plus 1 factorial is n plus 1
times n times n minus 1 times

00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:15.440
n minus 2 all the way down.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:17.630
So n plus 1 factorial--

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:23.450
I'll just write this here-- n
plus 1 factorial equals n plus

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:27.390
1 times n factorial.

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:30.470
That's very important that
you recognize that OK?

00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:33.030
Because the division of
factorials is a little more

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:35.890
complicated than the division
of straight polynomials or

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:36.510
something like this.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.410
Alright?

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:40.710
Because when I take this limit,
what am i going to get?

00:09:40.710 --> 00:09:43.350
I'm going to get x to the n
plus 1 over x to the n.

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:45.530
That's going to give me 1x.

00:09:45.530 --> 00:09:48.760
And then n factorial divided
by n plus 1 factorial, well

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:52.250
based on the fact that this is
equal to n plus 1 times n

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:56.610
factorial, the n factorials
divide, and I'm left with x

00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:57.940
over n plus 1.

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:01.480
That's actually what
this limit equals.

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:03.260
Let me go through that
one more time.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:05.860
This part is easy, x to the
n plus 1 over x to the m

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:08.390
gives me the x.

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:14.520
And then n factorial over n
plus 1 factorial is just 1

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:15.570
over n plus 1.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:17.580
And I have be careful because
I wrote equals, but there's

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:18.490
still an n here.

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:19.390
So let me erase that.

00:10:19.390 --> 00:10:22.990
I'm not gonna, I don't think, my
studio audience didn't say

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:24.610
anything yet, but I don't think
they were going to let

00:10:24.610 --> 00:10:25.890
me get away with that.

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:30.690
This is a limited as n goes to
infinity of x over n plus 1.

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:32.090
Now what is that?

00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:36.260
Well as n goes to infinity,
for any fixed x I pick--

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:39.370
we have to be careful here--
for any fixed x I pick as n

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:42.805
goes to infinity, this quantity
is equal to 0.

00:10:42.805 --> 00:10:45.140
OK?

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:48.180
If I were moving x around, if
I were moving x with n, this

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:50.020
will be a problem,
but x is fixed.

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:52.580
When I do this sum, I fix
my x at the beginning.

00:10:52.580 --> 00:10:58.080
So for any fixed x n plus 1 is
getting arbitrarily large.

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:00.820
So x over n plus 1 is getting
arbitrarily small.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:02.110
So this limit is 0.

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:04.360
This is strictly less than 1.

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:05.560
What does this mean?

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:08.587
For any x I pick, this whole
thing is less than 1.

00:11:08.587 --> 00:11:09.500
Right?

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:12.370
Any fixed x, this ratio
is always less than 1.

00:11:12.370 --> 00:11:13.100
What does that mean?

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:15.660
That means the radius of
convergence is infinite.

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:19.860
So the radius is infinity.

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:22.230
OK.

00:11:22.230 --> 00:11:26.070
The radius of convergence
is actually infinite.

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:28.530
What series is this?

00:11:28.530 --> 00:11:32.150
This is actually the Taylor
series for e to the x.

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:34.540
So we know that the Taylor
series for e to the x that

00:11:34.540 --> 00:11:36.926
this converges for any x.

00:11:36.926 --> 00:11:38.220
That's a nice thing.

00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:41.250
So now we've used the ratio test
to tell us how the Taylor

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.590
series behaves for a function
that we know.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:46.680
OK, we know its radius of
convergence is infinite.

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:48.210
So that's pretty nice.

00:11:48.210 --> 00:11:51.240
All right let's do maybe one
or two more examples,

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:56.010
depending on how much
room I have.

00:11:56.010 --> 00:11:59.760
OK, let's try this one.

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:04.430
x to the n over n times
2 to the n.

00:12:04.430 --> 00:12:07.990
All right, so this is another
power series we have. And we

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:11.695
want to know if I want to plug
in some value of x and I want

00:12:11.695 --> 00:12:14.970
to take the sum, will that
converge for that particular

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:15.790
value of x?

00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:18.620
We want to know what values
of x can I plug in.

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:22.173
All right so again, we're going
to look at the radius

00:12:22.173 --> 00:12:24.710
of, find the radius of
convergence based on the ratio

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:33.190
test. So the n plus first term
is x to the n plus 1 over n

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:37.580
plus 1 2 to the n plus 1.

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:41.760
And then I have to multiply by
the a sub m's, the a sub n

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:44.650
term, or multiply by
1 over that, sorry.

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:48.840
I'm dividing by a sub n, so
I get n times 2 to the n

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:51.410
over x to the n.

00:12:51.410 --> 00:12:54.551
All right, this gives me an x.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:59.910
n plus 1 over n, let me just
write out actually what we get

00:12:59.910 --> 00:13:04.340
here, 2 to the n over 2 to the
n plus 1 gives me an over 2.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:08.710
and then n over n plus 1.

00:13:08.710 --> 00:13:10.580
This is positive, so I
don't have to worry

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:12.700
about anything there.

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:16.520
The limit as n goes to infinity
absolute value of x

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:18.680
over 2 times n over n plus
1, what's that equal to?

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:21.040
Well this, as n goes to infinity
is equal to 1, so

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:24.060
it's absolute value
of x over 2.

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:25.510
Let me again remind you
what we are doing.

00:13:25.510 --> 00:13:28.760
We're saying I want to know the
radius of convergence for

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:29.530
this series.

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:32.780
So I want to know what radius,
so what values of x can I put

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:35.270
in to make this series
converge?

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:38.530
I might miss the endpoints, but
beyond that what values of

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:39.980
x make this series converge?

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:43.160
So I'm looking at the ratio
test. I took the ratio test, I

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:45.720
got it all the way to a place
where I have something in

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:46.890
terms of x.

00:13:46.890 --> 00:13:51.580
As long as that thing is less
than 1, I'm golden.

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:54.060
As long as that thing is less
than 1, the series converges.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:55.690
So again, I actually get
another thing where the

00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:59.030
absolute value of x
is less than 2.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:13:59.085
Alright?

00:13:59.085 --> 00:14:01.130
I probably should have picked
a different number there.

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:04.390
What do you think would happen
if this was a 7?

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:06.470
Well everything would've been
the same except this would

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:08.740
have been a 7, and the
radius of convergence

00:14:08.740 --> 00:14:10.130
would have been 7.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:12.360
So I should have picked a
different number there, so we

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:15.130
had a different radius of
convergence, but you can see

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:18.230
how that works.

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:19.160
And the, I'm gonna do just, I
have a room, I'm going to do

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:20.600
one more example.

00:14:20.600 --> 00:14:21.970
'Cause this one's a good
one to do also.

00:14:27.550 --> 00:14:32.250
OK, I'm actually going to do
another series that we know, x

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:35.450
to the 2n over 2n factorial.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:38.080
I'm doing this one for a
particular reason to help us

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:43.480
deal with when some things,
when the exponents and the

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:47.390
factorials get a little
more complicated.

00:14:47.390 --> 00:14:50.600
I want to also point out
what series is this.

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:52.810
You should know what
series this is.

00:14:52.810 --> 00:14:54.310
And I know, without thinking,
that it's

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.520
either sine or cosine.

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:58.460
I guess I should say
it's starting at

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:00.170
n equals 0 to infinity.

00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:02.460
And then I might get nervous and
say well, which one is it?

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:04.390
Well what's the first term?

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:07.460
x to the 0 is 1 over
0 factorial is 1.

00:15:07.460 --> 00:15:11.160
So it looks like the first term
is 1, so that makes me

00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:11.770
know it's cosine.

00:15:11.770 --> 00:15:12.950
Right?

00:15:12.950 --> 00:15:16.710
If the first term were x
I'd know it was sine.

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:18.250
So if I get nervous, so this,
where it converges, is equal

00:15:18.250 --> 00:15:19.770
to cosine x.

00:15:19.770 --> 00:15:21.020
Let's look at this one.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.010
All right, we got, now this you
have to be a little more

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:31.400
careful because it's 2 times the
quantity n plus 1 over 2n

00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:32.640
plus 2 factorial.

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:41.280
So that's n plus 1 times 2 is
2n plus 2 times 2n factorial

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:44.370
over x to the 2n.

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:46.550
All right this is where it might
get a little tricky.

00:15:46.550 --> 00:15:49.890
This is 2n plus 2
divided by 2n.

00:15:49.890 --> 00:15:54.480
So this is going to be the limit
as n goes to infinity of

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:57.980
x squared, the absolute value
squared which is just x

00:15:57.980 --> 00:16:00.050
squared again, times
this thing.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:02.100
So let's figure out what
this thing is.

00:16:02.100 --> 00:16:03.560
OK?

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:04.790
What is 2n factorial?

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:07.650
I'm going to write out the first
couple terms. OK, that's

00:16:07.650 --> 00:16:12.580
going to be 2n times 2n minus
1 times, that's all

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:14.490
the way down to 1.

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:15.150
And then what's this?

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:23.210
This is 2n plus 2 times 2n plus
1 times 2n times, all the

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:24.330
way down to 1.

00:16:24.330 --> 00:16:27.725
So we see, this is what I was
talking about earlier actually

00:16:27.725 --> 00:16:30.820
also, was that I've
added 2 to this.

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:34.280
So it's not surprising I get 2
more terms, and then I'm down

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:35.415
to 2n factorial again.

00:16:35.415 --> 00:16:35.830
Right?

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:37.520
So this 2n factorial.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:39.260
This is 2n factorial.

00:16:39.260 --> 00:16:41.820
So the 2n factorial here divides
with the 2n factorial

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:45.060
here, and I'm left
with these here.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:48.370
I get 1 over 2n plus
2 times 2n plus 1.

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:50.860
Now what happens as n
goes to infinity?

00:16:50.860 --> 00:16:53.410
Obviously this ratio
goes to 0.

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:56.010
So I'm actually in another case
similar to the one I saw

00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:57.910
with e to the x.

00:16:57.910 --> 00:16:58.890
Is that this goes to 0.

00:16:58.890 --> 00:17:01.040
So the limit is actually
equal to 0, which is

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:02.210
always less than 1.

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:04.670
Any value of x I pick
is less than 1.

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:06.940
And so this series actually
converges for

00:17:06.940 --> 00:17:09.850
any x that I pick.

00:17:09.850 --> 00:17:11.880
So this is another case where
I have the radius of

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:14.550
convergence is actually
infinite.

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:16.600
OK, so we'll probably give you
some problems where you have

00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:17.840
some other things happening.

00:17:17.840 --> 00:17:20.470
'Cause you can actually get the
radius convergence is 0.

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:23.000
You can actually get that the
only place it converges is at

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:23.850
x equals 0.

00:17:23.850 --> 00:17:26.960
So you might actually get
the limit as n goes

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:28.530
to infinity is infinity.

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:30.520
I didn't give you an example
of that, but that's a case

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:33.250
where whatever x value you
put in, your limit is

00:17:33.250 --> 00:17:34.930
still bigger than 1.

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:38.390
Then you would always get a
diverges, except when x is 0.

00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:41.200
OK, so that's another thing
that you can run into.

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:43.440
But, the point I want to make
is that this is going to let

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:46.030
us determine, you know, at least
the radius over which

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:47.810
these x values converge.

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:50.440
And it also helps us if we know
certain things about a

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:53.590
function to tell us where this
function is actually equal to

00:17:53.590 --> 00:17:56.470
the series that we're
dealing with.

00:17:56.470 --> 00:17:59.400
So I think that's where I'll
stop, and I hope this was

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:00.650
informative.